&gt; How would we stop a deadlock here if the function was called at the same time for `(a,b)` and `(b,a)`?

That&#39;s a scenario of catastrophe if there&#39;s a possibility for one thread to enter synchronized blocks in the reversed order relatively to another thread.

To avoid deadlocks, there should be the same order of monitor-objects in **every** method. To ensure that, you need to have a uniform logic of ordering the monitor objects based on their unique properties (and not on the order of the method arguments). I.e. to guaranty a consistent ordering, you need to decide which of the arguments should be used in the first synchronized section and which in the second.

Assuming that account looks like that:

    public class Account {
        public static final BinaryOperator&lt;Account&gt; FIRST = 
            BinaryOperator.maxBy(Comparator.comparing(Account::getId));
        
        public static final BinaryOperator&lt;Account&gt; SECOND =
            BinaryOperator.minBy(Comparator.comparing(Account::getId));
        private UUID id;
        // other properties and methods
    }

That&#39;s how `transfer()` method should look like:

    public void transferMoney(Account a, Account b, float value) {
        Account first = Account.FIRST.apply(a,b);
        Account second = Account.SECOND.apply(a,b);
        
        synchronized (first) {
            synchronized (second) {
                transfer();
            }
        }
    }

An alternative to using `synchronized` and monitor-objects would be to use [Locks][1]. The core idea remains the same: there should be no possibility for a thread to acquire one lock and wait for another lock indefinitely, instead such thread should release the lock it has acquired if it can&#39;t get all the locks needed to perform the action.

   [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/essential/concurrency/newlocks.html

