So, I found the solution to this particular issue after reading this article. https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/generics/capture.html

The problem is that when using wildcards the compiler cannot guarantee that  objects are of the correct type, but by using a generic helper method you can ensure type safety for each element by capturing the type of the wildcard. In this case, this is the helper method that I used.

    private &lt;T extends Component&gt; void addNewComponentInstance(Class&lt;T&gt; type, int uid){
        try {
            getParent().getComponentManager().add(type, uid, type.newInstance());
        } catch (Exception ex) {
            ex.printStackTrace();
        }
    }

And this is how it was sandwiched into the wildcard method.

    public Entity createEntity(Class&lt;? extends Component&gt;... types){
        Entity e = new Entity();  
        for(Class&lt;? extends Component&gt; type: types)
            addNewComponentInstance(type, e.UID);                   
        INDEX.add(e.UID, e);
        return e;
    }

This solution compiles and runs correctly.

